05736nam a22007815i 9780292795778DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927957787 a10.7560/7127372doi  a(DE-B1597)586740  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aBP170.5b.W66 2006eb 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a297.082/09182122200aWomen Embracing Islam :bGender and Conversion in the West /ced. by Karin van Nieuwkerk. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (308 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword. Conversion and Gender, Two Contested Concepts -- tIntroduction. Gender and Conversion to Islam in the West -- tPart one. Contextualizing Conversion -- tChapter 1. The Quest for Peace in Submission -- tChapter 2. The Shaping of a Scandinavian “Islam” -- tChapter 3. Symbolizing Distance -- tPart two. Discourses and Narratives -- tChapter 4. Gender, Conversion, and Islam -- tChapter 5. The Shifting Significance of the Halal/Haram Frontier -- tPart three. Trajectories and Paradigms -- tChapter 6. Female Conversion to Islam -- tChapter 7. African American Islam as an Expression of Converts’ Religious Faith and Nationalist Dreams and Ambitions -- tChapter 8. Feminism and Conversion -- tPart four. Transmission and Identity -- tChapter 9. How Deborah Became Aisha -- tChapter 10. Keeping the Faith -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany Westerners view Islam as a religion that restricts and subordinates women in both private and public life. Yet a surprising number of women in Western Europe and America are converting to Islam. What attracts these women to a belief system that is markedly different from both Western Christianity and Western secularism? What benefits do they gain by converting, and what are the costs? How do Western women converts live their new Islamic faith, and how does their conversion affect their families and communities? How do women converts transmit Islamic values to their children? These are some of the questions that Women Embracing Islam seeks to answer. In this vanguard study of gender and conversion to Islam, leading historians, sociologists, anthropologists, and theologians investigate why non-Muslim women in the United States, several European countries, and South Africa are converting to Islam. Drawing on extensive interviews with female converts, the authors explore the life experiences that lead Western women to adopt Islam, as well as the appeal that various forms of Islam, as well as the Nation of Islam, have for women. The authors find that while no single set of factors can explain why Western women are embracing Islamic faith traditions, some common motivations emerge. These include an attraction to Islam's high regard for family and community, its strict moral and ethical standards, and the rationality and spirituality of its theology, as well as a disillusionment with Christianity and with the unrestrained sexuality of so much of Western culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGender identityzEurope. 0aMuslim converts from ChristianityzEurope. 0aMuslim womenzEurope. 0aSex rolexReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aWomen in IslamzEurope. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aAllievi, Stefano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadran, Margot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourque, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaddad, Yvonne Yazbeck, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHermansen, Marcia, econtributo